In 2001, a secret memo concluded that President George W. Bush had broad authority to wage preemptive war against terrorists and nations, even without direct links to 9/11.
The memo argued for unlimited presidential power to use military force against terrorist organizations.
Democrats sought answers on issues like the detention of Jose Padilla and torture practices.
Alberto Gonzales faced scrutiny for his role in creating legal frameworks that led to abuses.
The debate over torture scandal involving John Yoo continues, with calls for accountability and transparency.
The need for a full investigation to restore America's reputation and uphold the rule of law remains pressing.
